Forgive me, for I will be blunt. Very blunt, and I dont wish to deter you from writting, but you require honesty to improve.

>A simple little bump-in
This feels really awkward to say without any kind of punctuation, and even with it
>between an uncle and a parent.and the wheels started turning.
Not only does this have a clear . where it shouldnt have but this wording is really confusing. Why is the main anon introduced as a random uncle literaly two lines in. The introduction itself feels somewhat rushed too.
>and even though she had a kid from a past relationship, she took after her mother a lot
We have no context of her mother, this is prety much saying nothing, confusing us at the most.
>One year of dating you popped the question,she said yes, after that:.
One big sin you do. Not putting a space after the , is a crime agaisnt literature itself and should have been combed over before even thinking of releasing the pastebin anon. This is just bad form.
>It hurts.
>It still hurts.
You were just talking about the past, then you do double present tense. You could do "It hurt then. It still hurts now." instead.
>But Holly really does take after her mom, in more than one way...
Elipses shoul really imply something more but dont seem to, and shouldnt it be "did take after her mom"?
>with a dad that skips town
This is another sin you do. Bad tenses mean flow is ruined. Keep the sentences going in the past or in the present, dont mix em, in here it should have been "with a dad that skipped town".

After these you do the same mistakes repeatedly, continuously. Your dialog, equaly, seems very slapped on and cobbled together, I wouldnt say full on awkward, but can you really say youd read it nd that it sounded anywhere normal? Anywhere conveying the emotions you want to show? Anywhere near what the quality it should be? >ladylava is also a bit of a wordsin anon.

Anonymous Mon 18 Nov 2019 23:30:03 No.26645484 Report
Quoted By: >>26646365
>>26644123

Seconded on the commas and sentence length.
You've got quite a few fragments. There's nothing wrong with fragments unless you want to go hardcore Strunk, but keep them under control. Things can feel complete because they mirror real speech without being verbally correct. Let them punch, like the staccato notes in a musical passage.
Unless you're a master or mistress of your thoughts don't go comma/semicolon crazy like LeGuin. They should earn their place, just like every usage of was/is. And on that subject - passive voice needs to earn its place as well.
If I woke up and saw that as part of last night's drunken output, here's how I might have edited lines 7-10
>All was truly well in the world.
>One year of dating you popped the question,she said yes, after that:.
>Two years of pure bliss.
>Two years of happiness with her and her daughter.
The world spun out three years of priceless bliss and happiness to warm you and them. It took a breathless year to admit life had woven them into your live, and that letting go would burn that fragile thread.

Then again, I tend to write longer sentences. I have arguments with the ghost of Hemingway on occasion when I get drunk enough

A story like this requires a substantial intelligence/technological/social gap between the humans and anthros.
